V. 1 Accidere autem in multis controversiis potest, ut ab utraque parte probabilia se ostendant argumenta, sive in- trinseca, sive ab aliorum auctoritate. Id cum accidit, si res mediocres sunt, de quibus agitur, videtur vitio carere posse electio, in utramvis partem occideret. At, si de re magni momenti, ut de supplicio capitali hominis, agitur, jam propter magnum discrimen, quod est inter eligenda, gpraeferenda est pars tutior, ut dici solet:

In istam partem potius peccato tamen.

Ideo satius est nocentem absolvere, quam innocentem con- demnare.

V. 1 It may happen, in many controversies, that probable argu- ments are adduced on both sides, either intrinsic to the subject, or derived from the authority of others. WVhen that happens, if the things in question are of moderate importance, the choice, it would seem, is free from blame, on whichever side it falls. But if there is question of a matter of great moment, as of a capital punishment, then, on account of the great difference between the two sides of the choice, the safer part is to be preferred. It is better to aequit a guilty man than to condemn an innocent.
